WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.160
Thank you so much, Dr. Cannon, for presenting this very important data.

00:00:06.700 --> 00:00:15.160
Now I would like to invite Dr. Tiger, Assistant Professor of Medicine at Mayo Clinic, to talk about the safety of peripheral IV anthracycline-based lymphoma regimen.

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:21.560
Hi, I'm Claire Tiger. Thank you so much for giving me the opportunity to present this data.

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:28.320
Actually, this was picked as a lender list number one last year at ASH 2025, so I'm very excited to share this data.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:36.500
Today, I'm going to tell you about the use and safety of peripheral IV versus central venous catheter for lymphoma patients receiving frontline anthracycline-based chemotherapy.

00:00:37.260 --> 00:00:44.560
My disclosures, extravasation of vesicants and infiltration of irritants are potential risks during anthracycline administration.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:50.620
To mitigate these risks, ports and picks are commonly used, but there are several limitations to using these.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.180
They require procedure replacement, so you need a surgeon or interventional radiologist.

00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:58.180
They can delay therapy.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:02.780
If you are not a surgeon or interventional radiologist, the patient may not be able to continue the treatment if you are not in the emergency room.

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:09.000
They can cause infections, thrombosis, and mechanical complications, and they certainly add health care costs.

00:01:10.140 --> 00:01:18.940
Before I go further into more details, I think it's really important to define these terms because extravasation is very loosely used in our field.

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:24.420
And so in order to do this study right, we went back to the literature and defined these terms very clearly.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:27.940
So extravasation is an extravenous administration.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:31.740
So extravasation is an extravenous administration of any vesicant solution that causes damage.

00:01:31.880 --> 00:01:38.920
So there is no to minimal blood return, usually associated with swelling, and they predominantly manifest with erythema.

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:44.800
Infiltration is an extravenous administration of non-vesicant solution.

00:01:45.960 --> 00:01:48.780
Phlebitis is inflammation of veins, inner lining.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:53.720
Flare reaction is a transient, painless, skin-streaking erythema.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:56.000
They usually resolve in one to two hours.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:01:57.920
And vessel irritation is a pain.

00:01:58.040 --> 00:01:58.300
Discomfort.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:03.280
For tightness along the infused vessels with erythema, dark skin discoloration.

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:10.320
So risk of extravasation injury is pretty uncommon and has been pretty well studied.

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:14.320
They vary in account from 0.01 to 6.5%.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:24.500
The biggest studies were encompassing all types of solid tumors and oncology in general that looked at over 730,000 infusions.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:28.000
And they documented 673 extravasation events.

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:30.360
Making up 0.09%.

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.880
The studies have also reported some patient-related risk factors with extravasation.

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:42.600
So advanced age, poor functional status, the quality of veins.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:50.980
And then there are operator and technical risk factors, such as limited experience, multiple attempts, and how fast you're infusing the chemotherapy.

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:57.600
In academic centers, PIV has been utilized for select frontline chemotherapy regulations.

00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:09.020
But because there's a lack of data on effectiveness and safety, a lot of the community centers and some of the academic centers default to using central venous catheter.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:18.780
So this study really is to look at complications of PIV versus central venous catheter in administering CHOP and AVVD-based chemotherapy.

00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:26.180
This was a multi-center retrospective study from eight U.S. centers, seven academic and one community.

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:27.920
And the use of PIV.

00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:31.020
PIV versus CBC was at center or provider discretion.

00:03:31.740 --> 00:03:38.820
This included patients over 18 with a newly diagnosed Hodgkin or non-Hodgkin lymphoma receiving CHOP or AVVD-based regimen.

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:40.960
Treated between 2010 to 2025.

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:45.280
If you were receiving continuous infusion like dosage of CDPOC, you were excluded.

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:49.040
And if you weren't receiving anthracycline, then you were also excluded.

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:51.420
Primary endpoint was extravasation.

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:56.060
Total, we looked at over 1,400 patients.

00:03:56.700 --> 00:03:57.580
CBC and PIV.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:01.340
In general, had the similar patient characteristics.

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:09.060
But I do have to point out that stage 3, 4 were higher in CBC arm and ECOG 0, 1 were higher in the PIV arm.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:13.040
In general, the types of lymphoma were very similar between the two arms.

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.840
And the types of chemotherapy that were administered between the two arms were very similar.

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:24.940
Three-fourths of patients from the CBC arm used the port-a-cath and a quarter of patients used the PIC.

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:27.600
So here is the data.

00:04:27.680 --> 00:04:33.600
In total, there were about 4,000 cycles in the CBC and 3,600 cycles in the PIV.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:39.000
And 4,900 infusions in the CBC and 4,400 in the PIV.

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:45.560
The reason there is a discrepancy between cycles and infusion is because AVVD have two infusions per cycle.

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:49.780
In total, there was only one extravasation reported in the PIV arm.

00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:57.560
This was a 70-year-old man who received polituzumab ARCHIP and had a chronic vascular damage with necrosis.

00:04:57.560 --> 00:04:59.000
It's requiring debridement and grafting.

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:01.620
So there was one case of chronic vascular damage.

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:04.740
There were two other cases of suspected extravasation.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:09.640
These were really limited information given the nature of retrospective data analysis.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.780
And we couldn't further analyze them.

00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:14.020
And so we put them under suspected extravasation.

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:16.420
But they did not have a chronic vascular damage.

00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:21.400
There was one case of infiltration with the CBC and six cases with the PIV.

00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:27.240
And there were six cases of flare in the PIV, but there were no documented vascular damage with these.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:36.500
There were higher incidence of DVT with the central venous catheter at 17 and four cases with the PIV.

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:39.260
And they all started anticoagulation.

00:05:39.860 --> 00:05:45.660
There was three cases of superficial venous thrombosis with PIV, which was treated with supportive care.

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:49.040
Now, you might ask, how do you account for DVT with the PIV?

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:52.440
That is a limitation of the retrospective.

00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:57.320
And so we basically said if you developed DVT in the upper extremity while you're getting the PIV,

00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:00.880
or getting chemotherapy, we counted that toward the DVT for the PIV arm.

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:07.200
The phlebitis was much higher in the PIV, and this was significantly higher.

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:10.920
The cellulitis and sepsis were higher in the CVC arm.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:15.540
There were five reported cases of sepsis with the CVC, but none reported with the PIV.

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:23.320
Erythema, swelling, catheter malfunction were similar, but pain was significantly higher with the PIV arm.

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:27.120
There were a total of 163 patients that switched.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:32.900
Between one modality to another, 129 received the PIV, then switched to CVC.

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:38.180
The reasons for switching were really limited based on the nature of retrospective.

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:42.660
And so there were significant patients that were not reported for the reasons why they changed.

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:51.180
Because age was one of the risk factors for extravasation, we did do a subgroup analysis for patients over 80 years old.

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:54.160
This group was a little bit smaller.

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:56.160
So CVC had an 89 patient.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:06:57.040
PIV arm.

00:06:57.080 --> 00:06:58.420
PIV arm had 122 patients.

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:06.500
In general, they were pretty similar in nature and in terms of their types of lymphoma and the chemotherapy that they received.

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:17.340
And there were 400 cycles in the CVC arm, 577 in the PIV arm, and 425 infusions in the CVC and 587 in the PIV arm.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:20.220
There were no extravasation that was reported.

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:26.420
And the one case of suspected extravasation was the same one that we had reported previously in the entire cohort.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:28.820
There were no chronic vascular damage.

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:35.660
There were one cases each of the infiltration of chemotherapy, two cases of flare and phlebitis in the PIV arm.

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:41.220
But there were higher cases of cellulitis and DVT in the CVC arm compared to the PIV arm.

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:50.120
This is a limited number, but PIV seems to have a similar safety profile as the CVC and appears to be a safe option even for elderly population.

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:56.840
So in total, I have looked at over 1,400 lymphoma patients and over 9,300.

00:07:56.840 --> 00:07:58.620
There were over 1,400 anthracycline treatment infusions.

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:07.140
Only one confirmed case of extravasation and chronic vascular damage was reported, making up 0.02% of all total infusions.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:10.760
Other than that, there were no other reported vascular damages.

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:17.220
And there were fewer DVTs and sepsis associated with PIVs compared to CVC, but more pain and phlebitis.

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:25.400
So use of PIV is safe and it appears to be an effective option for anthracycline-based regimen for treatment of lymphoma.

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:28.560
my acknowledgement.
